<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1"><title>Wylib Paragraph Widget</title><meta name="generator" content="DocBook XSL Stylesheets V1.79.1"></head><body bgcolor="white" text="black" link="#0000FF" vlink="#840084" alink="#0000FF"><div class="article"><div class="titlepage"><div><div><h2 class="title"><a name="Wylib%20Pref"></a>Wylib Paragraph Widget</h2></div></div><hr></div><div class="toc"><p><b>Table of Contents</b></p><dl class="toc"><dt><span class="sect1"><a href="#idm140407999842752">Introduction</a></span></dt><dt><span class="sect1"><a href="#idm140407999840496">Standard Fields</a></span></dt></dl></div><div class="sect1"><div class="titlepage"><div><div><h2 class="title" style="clear: both"><a name="idm140407999842752"></a>Introduction</h2></div></div></div><p>
   The paragraph Embedded Text Widget (ETW) allows you to produce a number
   of paragraphs within your document that are formatted like an outline.
  </p><p>
   For example, sometimes it is desirable to create a set of numbered
   paragraphs. 
   Although this widget does not do automatic numbering, it does take care
   of indenting the paragraphs correctly.
  </p><p>
   Like all ETW's, there is a main menu in the upper left part of the widget
   where all the widget's functionality can be accessed.
  </p></div><div class="sect1"><div class="titlepage"><div><div><h2 class="title" style="clear: both"><a name="idm140407999840496"></a>Standard Fields</h2></div></div></div><div class="variablelist"><dl class="variablelist"><dt><span class="term">(Indent level)</span></dt><dd><p>
        This entry contains a number and indicates how many levels deep this
        paragraph should be intended.
        For example, the first paragraph, and all paragraphs like it should 
        be numbered "1".
        Sub-paragraphs of these paragraphs should be numbered "2".
        Sub-sub-paragraphs should be numbered "3", etc.
       </p><p>
        These indent levels can be incremented or decremented with the spinner buttons just to the right of the entry.
       </p></dd><dt><span class="term">(Title)</span></dt><dd><p>
        This entry (the larger one on the right) can contain an optional
        title that will be shown at the beginning of the paragraph.
        The title, if present, will hang out to the left of the paragraph
        when formatted.
       </p><p>
        For example, main paragraphs, might have titles: 1., 2., 3., etc.
        For example, sub-paragraphs, might have titles: a., b., c., and so on.
       </p></dd></dl></div></div></div></body></html>
